{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654633"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:53:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18622"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18622","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18622"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11354"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76479"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11354"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18622"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61976"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10267"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26348"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26355"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76479"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring high-intensity exercise, skeletal muscle requires rapid access to energy stores to maintain contractile function.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of creatine phosphate in skeletal muscle energy metabolism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Produces acetyl-CoA for oxidation","Facilitates fatty acid breakdown","Stores calcium in sarcoplasmic reticulum","Generates glucose through gluconeogenesis","Transfers phosphate group to ADP to form ATP"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECreatine phosphate plays a crucial role in skeletal muscle energy metabolism by \u003Cstrong\u003Etransferring its phosphate group to ADP to form ATP\u003C/strong\u003E. This reaction is catalysed by creatine kinase and provides a rapid source of ATP during high-intensity exercise when energy demands suddenly increase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenerates glucose through gluconeogenesis\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs primarily in the liver, not in skeletal muscle\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduces acetyl-CoA for oxidation\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the role of pyruvate dehydrogenase in glucose metabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitates fatty acid breakdown\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs through beta oxidation in mitochondria\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStores calcium in sarcoplasmic reticulum\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the role of calcium ATPase pumps\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe creatine phosphate system can rapidly replenish ATP stores but can only sustain maximal muscle contraction for approximately 10-15 seconds before other energy systems must take over.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Creatine phosphate serves as a rapid energy source by transferring its phosphate group to ADP to form ATP during high-intensity exercise.","The creatine phosphate energy system can sustain maximal muscle contraction for 10-15 seconds.","Creatine kinase catalyses the reversible transfer of phosphate between creatine and ATP."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"6197